Today's Research Reports on Stocks to Watch: United Continental Holdings and CSX Corporation


By AccessWire,  July 20, 2017, 08:10:00 AM EDT








Vote up







A
A
A









NEW YORK, NY / ACCESSWIRE / July 20, 2017 / Transportation stocks had a bloody day on Wednesday with the Dow Jones Transportation Average DJT falling 57 points. CSX Corporation was one of the biggest railroad stocks to drop. United Continental Holdings was the biggest loser of all of the transportation stocks and accounted for a big chunk of the DJT's fall yesterday.
RDI Initiates Coverage on:
United Continental Holdings, Inc.https://ub.rdinvesting.com/news/?ticker=UAL
CSX Corporationhttps://ub.rdinvesting.com/news/?ticker=CSX
United Continental Holdings, Inc., the parent of United Airlines, closed down 5.91% on Wednesday after the company revealed a weak forecast for the rest of the summer. In a conference call yesterday, the company announced that third-quarter passenger unit revenue could be negative for the third quarter. Considering that this revenue measure had seen a 2.1% growth from April through June, traders were less than impressed. The parent of United Airlines is still suffering from backlash after dragging a passenger off one of its planes. CEO Oscar Munoz remains optimistic however and stated, "From investing in our products and our people, redoubling our focus on the customer experience, closing the margin gap with our peers and delivering strong returns to our investors, we have made important progress and moved United decisively forward." He also reminded, "No single quarter constitutes a trend and we still have much further to go before we fully realize the potential of this airline and exceed the expectations of our customers."
Access RDI'sUnited Continental Holdings Research Report at: https://ub.rdinvesting.com/news/?ticker=UAL
CSX Corporation closed in the red yesterday with shares down 5.91%. Despite beating its earnings expectations, investors were wary on how the company did it. For the second quarter, CSX reported a 14% improvement in reported operating profit. New CEO Hunter Harrison has been leading the company in a turnaround and has spent $122 million in restructuring charges. He commented, "Although there still remains a lot to be done, we are confident that these initiatives will drive improved customer service, greater resource efficiency, and superior shareholder value." Harrison has helped turnarounds at three other railroads already. Had it not been for these charges, however, CSX would have reported earnings per share of 64 cents. This beat the 59 cents that analysts had been looking for. Traders were also discouraged by the company's outlook. The railroad reiterated a forecast of 25 percent improvement over last year's earnings per share of $1.81. Analysts surveyed by FactSet had forecast adjusted annual earnings per share of $2.29 for the year.
Access RDI'sCSX Corporation Research Report at: https://ub.rdinvesting.com/news/?ticker=CSX
Our Actionable Research on United Continental Holdings, Inc. (NYSE:UAL) and CSX Corporation (NASDAQ:CSX) can be downloaded free of charge at Research Driven Investing.
