United Continental Holdings Inc (UAL): Immense Growth Potential?



Brandon Murphy 


            				July 18, 2017			        


 With 31.3% predicted earnings growth over the next year United Continental Holdings Inc (NYSE:UAL) seems to be a well performing company. What are the important facts you need to know? I’m going to investigate the latest data and look into some metrics you shouldn’t overlook. View our latest analysis for United Continental Holdings 
Exciting times ahead for UAL
 Investors in United Continental Holdings have been patiently waiting for the uptick in earnings and if you believe the 8 analysts covering the stock then the next 3 years will be very interesting. The estimates for earnings per share range from $10.15 to $11.69 with an average expectation of 66.7% growth. 
 

 United Continental Holdings (NYSE:UAL) Past Future Earnings Jul 18th 17
 
                         Note that the expectation is still for earnings to be below the average of the past couple of years. 
 In the same period we will see the revenue grow from $36.78 Billion to $43.25 Billion in 2020 and profit is predicted to escalate from $2.05 Billion to $2.96 Billion in 2020, roughly growing 1.4x. Margins are expected to be not high but still acceptable at 6.8% during this time as well. 
Basis for the growth
 United Continental Holdings has underperformed compared to the Transportation industry, even worse considering the industry in general has had a tough year. 
 The team behind United Continental Holdings appears to be doing a pretty good job over the last year with an Return on Equity of 25.1%, despite this being below the average for the Transportation industry of 46.82%. This is expected to further improve with the stock estimated to have an outstanding ROE of 25.8%.


 United Continental Holdings (NYSE:UAL) Future Perf Jul 18th 17


 Return on equity (ROE) is a measure of how much profit (net income) a company makes as a percentage of the shareholders equity. Equity is made up of funds from the original issuing of shares and any retained earnings from previous financial years. It varies considerably across sectors, for this reason it is important to asses a stocks ROE relative to its industry. Whilst it is true that the higher the ROE the better the company is performing, ROE does have a weakness. A stock with a disproportionate amount of debt can lead to a small equity base. Thus, a small amount of net income (the numerator) could still produce a high ROE off a modest equity base (the denominator). For this reason investors should always consider the debt situation in conjunction with ROE. 
Final words
 United Continental Holdings is a fast growing company, but as Warren Buffett’s right-hand man Charlie Munger said, “No matter how wonderful a business is, it’s not worth an infinite price“. Is UAL overpriced? Or could it be considered an undervalued opportunity? I recommend you see our latest FREE analysis to find out!
 If you are not interested in UAL anymore, you can use our free platform to see my list of over 150 other stocks with a high growth potential. 
